ied part of the whole network, so reducing steps does not improve plausibility enough.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "suggestions": ["Retain the simplified topology but replace speculative convergence chemistry.", "Add intermediary validated compounds between pyruvate and the proposed histidine precursor.", "Specify phosphorylation state and leaving groups needed for condensation."]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.78, "rxn_003": 0.62, "rxn_004": 0.58, "rxn_005": 0.84, "rxn_006": 0.32, "rxn_007": 0.88, "rxn_008": 0.28, "rxn_009": 0.74, "rxn_010": 0.38, "rxn_011": 0.12, "rxn_012": 0.08}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.45, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.84, "target_achievement": 0.2, "overall_confidence": 0.5, "feedback": "This is the best-connected and most redundant route, and it best demonstrates hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical flow. However, the same core issue remains: the final three reactions are too speculative to justify histidine as an achieved target. The pathway is strong as a feedstock network, weak as a complete synthesis route.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "suggestions": ["Reframe the network as a precursor network to histidine-related chemistry unless a supported terminal route is added.", "Provide mineral agents explicitly for all hydrothermal and surface steps; current summary omits them.", "Anchor late-stage reactions to known biosynthetic analogs only if nonenzymatic counterparts are defensible."]}], "best_pathway_id": "P10", "overall_confidence": 0.49, "network_feedback": "The network is topologically decent: it has enough molecule and reaction nodes, several true hubs, multiple convergent branches, and a connected Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical architecture. Early and mid-stage chemistry is moderately plausible, especially CO2 reduction to formate, acetate-related carbon fixation, pyruvate formation, alanine formation, HCN oligomerization to adenine, and borate-assisted sugar chemistry. The major weakness is target achievement. Histidine is not credibly produced by the final assembly sequence. Reactions converting ribose to amino-ribose phosphate, imidazole plus amino-ribose phosphate plus pyruvate to a histidine precursor, and the final precursor plus alanine to histidine are highly speculative, lack clear atom-economic logic, and are not established prebiotic routes. Environmental interconnection is present conceptually, but the provided network summary does not specify mineral agents for each hydrothermal and surface reaction, which is a formal deficiency under the stated schema. Overall, this is a plausible precursor network feeding histidine-related chemistry, but not a convincing complete synthesis network to histidine.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.82, "convergence_quality": 0.77}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 84336.05885505676, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T19:32:35.044620", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Histidine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.49\n- Feedback: The network is topologically decent: it has enough molecule and reaction nodes, several true hubs, multiple convergent branches, and a connected Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical architecture. Early and mid-stage chemistry is moderately plausible, especially CO2 reduction to formate, acetate-related carbon fixation, pyruvate formation, alanine formation, HCN oligomerization to adenine, and borate-assisted sugar chemistry. The major weakness is target achievement. Histidine is not credibly produced by the final assembly sequence. Reactions converting ribose to amino-ribose phosphate, imidazole plus amino-ribose phosphate plus pyruvate to a histidine precursor, and the final precursor plus alanine to histidine are highly speculative, lack clear atom-economic logic, and are not established prebiotic routes. Environmental interconnection is present conceptually, but the provided network summary does not specify mineral agents for each hydrothermal and surface reaction, which is a formal deficiency under the stated schema. Overall, this is a plausible precursor network feeding histidine-related chemistry, but not a convincing complete synthesis network to histidine.\n- Issues: ['Early hydrothermal carbon-fixation logic is plausible, and the hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical progression is conceptually connected. However, the route breaks down in the late-stage assembly: amino-ribose phosphate formation is underspecified, the imidazole/amino-ribose/pyruvate coupling is highly speculative, and the final conversion to histidine lacks a chemically credible mechanism.', 'The sugar branch is one of the more coherent parts of the network, with formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde feeding borate-stabilized formose chemistry. Still, the route depends on weakly supported translation from ribose to amino-ribose phosphate and then to a histidine precursor. The final target synthesis remains unconvincing.', 'HCN-first convergence is plausible for adenine generation, and HCN is a valid network hub. But using HCN/formamide chemistry to access free imidazole under the stated step is weakly defined, and the transition from nitrogen heterocycles to histidine is the dominant failure point.', 'The adenine-assisted route is the weakest coherent pathway because adenine is formed credibly from HCN oligomerization but no convincing chemistry is provided showing how adenine assists histidine assembly. This appears topologically connected but chemically decorative rather than functionally necessary.', 'Using alanine as a late amino donor is somewhat more sensible than some alternatives, since alanine can participate in transamination-like chemistry. Even so, the network never defines a realistic acceptor corresponding to a histidinol/histidinal or imidazole-pyruvate analog. Thus the late transamination idea is incomplete.', 'Formamide chemistry is prebiotically relevant, but the specific conversion from formamide plus HCN to free imidazole is insufficiently grounded. The pathway inherits the same late-stage failures as the others and does not convincingly solve the key heterocycle-to-amino-acid construction problem.', 'A carbonyl-rich hydrothermal entry is a reasonable way to populate formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and pyruvate hubs. The issue is not early feedstock generation but unsupported elaboration to histidine. The network is strongest up to central carbon intermediates and weakest after sugar/heterocycle convergence.', 'The adenine-parallel surface chemistry route demonstrates network redundancy but not stronger target synthesis. Adenine remains a side product disconnected from productive histidine-forming chemistry, so redundancy here is topological rather than chemically useful.', 'This minimal convergence route is topologically cleaner than the longer alternatives and better highlights the intended sugar-heterocycle-ketoacid merge. Nevertheless, the convergence itself is chemically the least justified part of the whole network, so reducing steps does not improve plausibility enough.', 'This is the best-connected and most redundant route, and it best demonstrates hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical flow. However, the same core issue remains: the final three reactions are too speculative to justify histidine as an achieved target. The pathway is strong as a feedstock network, weak as a complete synthesis route.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Histidine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets histidine through a chemically conservative prebiotic strategy that avoids unsupported direct assembly from free imidazole and ribose. Instead, it builds a dense precursor network around four hubs\u2014HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and pyruvate\u2014generated in hydrothermal and surface settings. Surface cyanide chemistry produces aminonitriles and imidazole-family nitriles; hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies pyruvate and simple carbonyls; biochemical steps then use hydrolysis, reductive amination, transamination, and condensation to access histidine or closely related histidine-precursor pools. Because no universally accepted fully prebiotic histidine synthesis exists, the final imidazole-alanine coupling sequence is explicitly marked as speculative but constrained to plausible precursor classes: imidazole-containing aldehydes/nitriles plus amino-acid-forming chemistry. The ten pathways are distinct traversals of this connected bipartite network rather than ten wholly disjoint chemistries.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanedinitrile diamide precursor class\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN-like HCN tetramer\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-2-5-3-4-1/h1-3H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazole-4-carbaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H7N3O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazolyl pyruvate analog\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H9N3O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"histidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl equivalents that hydrolyze to formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe-S minerals catalyze reduction of CO2 to simple C1 products under hydrothermal conditions and provide a plausible entry to prebiotic carbon fixation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Magnetite/iron-mediated reduction of CO2-derived C1 pool to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"380-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise hydrogenation of C1 oxides/formate on iron oxide and Fe0 surfaces yields reduced carbonyl species including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and related hydrothermal reductions produce reduced carbonyl compounds from C1 feedstocks; formaldehyde is a plausible low-abundance member of this product pool (Horita & Berndt, 1999; McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-430K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent pore system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-promoted reductive coupling of reduced C1 species generates a C2 hydroxyaldehyde pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"While exact glycolaldehyde yields are system-dependent, hydrothermal Fe-mineral catalysis can access small oxygenated C2 organics from reduced carbon sources; this step is moderately speculative but serves as a chemically conservative bridge to surface sugar chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from reduced carbon pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential carboxylation and reduction on Fe-S/Fe-oxide surfaces expands the C2 carbonyl pool to an alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is among the more plausible prebiotic alpha-keto acid hubs in hydrothermal proto-metabolic proposals, supported by iron-sulfur-mediated carbon fixation logic though direct high-yield synthesis remains challenging (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surface, NH3 available\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid imine formation followed by mineral-assisted reduction yields the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Amino acid formation from alpha-keto acids via reductive amination/transamination is central to prebiotic metabolic network models; alanine from pyruvate is among the most chemically plausible examples (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface generation of HCN from reduced carbon and ammonia under UV-active mineral conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, evaporitic concentration, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical dehydration/oxidation-state reorganization of reduced C/N feedstocks yields cyanide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a central surface feedstock in prebiotic chemistry and plausibly arises photochemically from reduced carbon and nitrogen species in anoxic settings; mineral photochemistry can assist concentration and redox processing (Stribling & Miller, 1987; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN-like tetramer pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling with UV exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentration-driven cyanide oligomerization forms aminomalononitrile and diaminomaleonitrile-type tetramers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN and related tetramers is a classic prebiotic route to nitrogen heterocycles and nitriles (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Sanchez et al., 1967).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical conversion of HCN tetramer pool to imidazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, partial hydrolysis in shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyclization and hydrolytic rearrangement of oligomerized nitriles yields imidazole-family heterocycles including imidazole.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Imidazole derivatives are known products within HCN/formamide-derived heterocycle chemistry, though direct free-imidazole yields vary; this step is plausible but less directly established than adenine formation (Saladino et al., 2007; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic synthesis of aminoimidazole carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox cyanide chemistry with small carbonyl compounds yields aminoimidazole-type nitriles through nitrile addition, reduction, and cyclization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanosulfidic chemistry links HCN, sulfide, UV light, and simple carbonyls to amino-oxazole and aminoimidazole intermediates relevant to nucleotide and heterocycle synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde addition to imidazole gives imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration, mild heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrophilic hydroxymethylation/oxidation-state adjustment of imidazole furnishes imidazole carbaldehyde derivatives.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formylated and hydroxymethylated imidazole derivatives are chemically accessible from imidazole and C1 carbonyl chemistry under dehydrating surface conditions; exact regioselectivity is uncertain, so this step is moderately speculative but avoids the less credible ribose-imidazole coupling used in failed attempts (Saladino et al., 2007; Becker et al., 2019 for prebiotic carbonyl-heterocycle reactivity).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical condensation of imidazole aldehyde with pyruvate/ammonia to imidazolyl pyruvate analog\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling, concentrated pools, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldimine formation and C-C bond construction between an imidazole aldehyde and alpha-keto acid chemistry gives an imidazole-substituted alpha-keto acid precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a necessary but speculative bridge to histidine. It is more chemically grounded than the rejected ribose/amino-ribose route because it uses a known amino-acid precursor class\u2014alpha-keto acids\u2014together with an imidazole aldehyde that can plausibly undergo Strecker-like or aldol/imine chemistry. The step addresses the core target-formation gap explicitly rather than disguising it (speculative; justified by analogy to alpha-keto acid amino acid synthesis and heteroaryl carbonyl chemistry).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination/reductive amination of imidazolyl pyruvate analog to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or mineral interface, repeated heating/cooling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine serves as amino donor in transamination-like exchange to convert the imidazole-bearing alpha-keto acid into histidine while regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final step is speculative but chemically disciplined: histidine is formed from an imidazole-substituted alpha-keto acid by the same logic that many amino acids derive from keto acids via transamination. Regeneration of pyruvate increases network coherence and gives pyruvate true hub character. No strong direct prebiotic literature exists for histidine specifically, so this gap is acknowledged rather than hidden (speculative; analogy to prebiotic transamination chemistry in Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction supplies formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, and alanine; HCN oligomerization yields imidazole, which is formylated and coupled into the histidine keto-acid precursor before transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Short HCN-imidazole route\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses hydrothermal formaldehyde to generate HCN directly, then proceeds through imidazole and the alpha-keto acid precursor.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde-assisted cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide chemistry uses hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to reach aminoimidazole carbonitrile before feeding the shared imidazole-containing pool and onward to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-rich entry route\",\n      \"description\": \"Starts from hydrothermal formate production, then branches to both formaldehyde and pyruvate before converging on imidazole aldehyde chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-first route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis emphasizes pyruvate and alanine generation before the surface heterocycle branch catches up to provide the imidazole aldehyde partner.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    