per CO2 hydrogenation and carbonyl generation; this step is retained as a necessary but moderately speculative bridge to surface sugar chemistry (He et al., 2010; Roldan et al., 2015; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C-C coupling to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent micropores with pH gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-bound C1 species undergo reductive carbonyl coupling to acetyl-like intermediates that hydrolyze to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe-S-mediated acetyl-thioester/acetate formation is central to iron-sulfur world models and supplies a plausible C2 hydrothermal product feeding keto-acid synthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from fixed carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal flow; carbon fixation analog of rTCA entry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Progressive reductive carboxylation and C-C bond formation from C1/C2 feedstocks furnish alpha-keto acids including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is an especially valuable hub because it connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to amino acid and side-chain synthesis; Fe-mediated abiotic formation of pyruvate and related rTCA intermediates has experimental precedent, though yields remain modest (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surface; NH3-rich microenvironment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia is followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is a plausible route from hydrothermal carbon fixation products to amino acids and provides an amino donor for later transamination chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN/formamide pool from simple C1 carbonyls\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, anoxic evaporitic pool, intermittent drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven oxidation-reduction and dehydration chemistry in carbonyl-ammonia systems generates cyanide and formamide reservoirs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct local HCN production from simple carbonyl/ammonia chemistry is less secure than atmospheric delivery, so this node represents a surface concentration and photochemical conversion module consistent with cyanide-rich prebiotic scenarios; formamide is included because it links HCN chemistry to heterocycle production (Sutherland, 2016; Saladino et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface borate-stabilized formation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool; wet-dry concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formose-like carbonyl oligomerization generates C2 and C3 sugars, with borate selectively stabilizing useful aldose products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are among the strongest prebiotic sugar-entry points; borate stabilization helps channel otherwise messy formose chemistry toward persistent intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol elaboration of sugars to ribose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate and clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation-concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation and rearrangement among C2/C3 aldehydes furnish pentose sugars, with borate favoring ribose persistence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ribose itself is fragile, but borate-assisted pentose stabilization is a standard route to connect carbonyl chemistry with nucleotide-related heterocycles and is retained here as a convergence node rather than a committed nucleotide branch (Ricardo et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic conversion of glycolaldehyde and HCN to aminoimidazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and UV-active TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, anoxic cyanosulfidic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide addition, reductive rearrangement, and ring closure in a cyanosulfidic mixture generate aminoimidazole-class heterocycles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminoimidazole-family intermediates, especially aminoimidazole carbonitrile derivatives, are well embedded in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry; representing this step as aminoimidazole production avoids the weaker claim of free imidazole directly arising in one jump while still connecting to histidine-like side-chain chemistry (Powner et al., 2009; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN/formamide heterocycle chemistry to imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted drying lagoon; concentrated formamide-rich films\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminoimidazole-class heterocycles undergo carbonylation/formylation and rearrangement in formamide-rich media to yield imidazole aldehyde derivatives.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a bottleneck step but chemically better defined than previous unsupported free-imidazole routes because it starts from aminoimidazole-class material rather than bare HCN oligomers; formamide-mediated heterocycle functionalization is experimentally established in related systems, though specific access to imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde under prebiotic conditions remains partly speculative (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic condensation of imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde with pyruvate to imidazole pyruvate analog\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interface\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required beyond mineral interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling; dehydration-rehydration; concentrated alpha-keto acid pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/knoevenagel-like carbon-carbon bond formation followed by redox adjustment gives an imidazole-substituted alpha-keto acid analogous to enzymatic imidazolepyruvate intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is explicitly speculative but chemically constrained: histidine is most plausibly approached through an imidazole-substituted alpha-keto acid rather than direct stitching of histidine from unrelated fragments. The network therefore adopts a keto-acid precursor consistent with known biochemical logic, acknowledging the lack of direct prebiotic experimental demonstration.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic transamination of imidazole pyruvate analog to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interface\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required beyond mineral interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool; repeated heating/cooling; alanine as amino donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reversible transamination transfers the amino group from alanine to the imidazole-substituted alpha-keto acid, regenerating pyruvate and yielding histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Among late-stage options, transamination of an alpha-keto acid analog is the chemically clearest way to obtain histidine because it uses a standard amino acid-forming logic already plausible prebiotically for simpler systems. This final step remains speculative for the histidine-specific substrate but is more atom-economical and mechanistically coherent than previous direct condensation proposals.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal carbon fixation to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate, extended to acetate and pyruvate, then merged with the HCN-derived imidazole branch and finished by transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-first sugar-assisted histidine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds surface sugar chemistry, generating glycolaldehyde before cyanosulfidic access to aminoimidazole and late-stage histidine assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Ribose-associated heterocycle pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde enters borate-stabilized sugar chemistry through glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to ribose, while the same carbonyl pool supports aminoimidazole generation before convergence onto the histidine precursor.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-first transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal chemistry prioritizes pyruvate and alanine formation, then a separately generated imidazole aldehyde side-chain precursor is attached and aminated.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-rich heterocycle route\",\n      \"description\": \"A surface HCN/formamide reservoir is used to reach imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde, which then condenses with hydrothermal pyruvate and undergoes transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde-convergent route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde is funneled into glycolaldehyde, which serves both sugar chemistry and aminoimidazole formation before final keto-acid assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-supported carbon fixation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate acts as the key C2 relay toward pyruvate, while surface cyanosulfidic chemistry independently prepares the imidazole branch for convergence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine-amino donor emphasized route\",\n      \"description\": \"This route foregrounds hydrothermal alanine production as a reusable amino donor for the final histidine-forming transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Ribose-parallel convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Sugar chemistry proceeds to ribose in parallel to heterocycle generation, illustrating network density even though ribose is not directly consumed in the final histidine step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal connected histidine route\",\n      \"description\": \"A shortest connected route still preserving environmental interconnection: hydrothermal pyruvate plus surface aminoimidazole/imidazole aldehyde chemistry converge on the imidazole pyruvate analog and then histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Histidine", "overall_strategy": "This network treats histidine as emerging from convergence of four experimentally better-motivated prebiotic modules rather than from a single unsupported direct route: (1) hydrothermal carbon fixation generates formate, acetate, pyruvate, and simple carbonyls; (2) surface cyanosulfidic and formose chemistry produces glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, ribose, and amino nitrile pools; (3) HCN-derived imidazole chemistry furnishes aminoimidazole and imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde-like heterocyclic precursors; and (4) biochemical/prebiotic transamination and condensation steps assemble an imidazole-substituted alpha-keto acid, then histidine. The late-stage histidine-forming steps are explicitly marked as speculative bottlenecks, but they are built around chemically clearer motifs than previous failed attempts: Strecker access to alpha-amino functionality, imidazole-carboxaldehyde as a side-chain precursor, and transamination of an imidazole-pyruvate analog to histidine. Multiple distinct pathways are created by combining alternative entries to shared hubs: HCN, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, ribose, aminoimidazole, and imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid/acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H10O5", "iupac_name": "pentose", "common_name": "ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h2-10H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H5N3", "iupac_name": "4-amino-1H-imidazole", "common_name": "aminoimidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5N3/c4-3-1-5-2-6-3/h1-2H,(H3,4,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H4N2O", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole-4-carbaldehyde", "common_name": "imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N2O/c7-3-4-1-5-2-6-4/h1-3H,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H6N2O3", "iupac_name": "3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "imidazole pyruvate analog", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H9N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "PO4H3", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to adsorbed formyl/formate equivalents on iron-sulfur phases.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the best supported hydrothermal entry reactions and provides a key C1 hub for downstream carbonyl chemistry (Herschy et al., 2014; Barge et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of CO2/formate pool to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing subseafloor setting; low water activity at mineral interface"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction of C1 oxides at reactive iron surfaces yields reduced carbonyl species including formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Direct formaldehyde accumulation in hydrothermal systems is less secure than formate, but reduced iron and magnetite can drive deeper CO2 hydrogenation and carbonyl generation; this step is retained as a necessary but moderately speculative bridge to surface sugar chemistry (He et al., 2010; Roldan et al., 2015; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal C-C coupling to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent micropores with pH gradient"}, "mechanism": "Surface-bound C1 species undergo reductive carbonyl coupling to acetyl-like intermediates that hydrolyze to acetate.", "reasoning": "Fe-S-mediated acetyl-thioester/acetate formation is central to iron-sulfur world models and supplies a plausible C2 hydrothermal product feeding keto-acid synthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from fixed carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal flow; carbon fixation analog of rTCA entry"}, "mechanism": "Progressive reductive carboxylation and C-C bond formation from C1/C2 feedstocks furnish alpha-keto acids including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is an especially valuable hub because it connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to amino acid and side-chain synthesis; Fe-mediated abiotic formation of pyruvate and related rTCA intermediates has experimental precedent, though yields remain modest (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic mineral surface; NH3-rich microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia is followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is a plausible route from hydrothermal carbon fixation products to amino acids and provides an amino donor for later transamination chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN/formamide pool from simple C1 carbonyls", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, anoxic evaporitic pool, intermittent drying"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven oxidation-reduction and dehydration chemistry in carbonyl-ammonia systems generates cyanide and formamide reservoirs.", "reasoning": "Direct local HCN production from simple carbonyl/ammonia chemistry is less secure than atmospheric delivery, so this node represents a surface concentration and photochemical conversion module consistent with cyanide-rich prebiotic scenarios; formamide is included because it links HCN chemistry to heterocycle production (Sutherland, 2016; Saladino et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface borate-stabilized formation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool; wet-dry concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Formose-like carbonyl oligomerization generates C2 and C3 sugars, with borate selectively stabilizing useful aldose products.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are among the strongest prebiotic sugar-entry points; borate stabilization helps channel otherwise messy formose chemistry toward persistent intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface aldol elaboration of sugars to ribose", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporation-concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation and rearrangement among C2/C3 aldehydes furnish pentose sugars, with borate favoring ribose persistence.", "reasoning": "Ribose itself is fragile, but borate-assisted pentose stabilization is a standard route to connect carbonyl chemistry with nucleotide-related heterocycles and is retained here as a convergence node rather than a committed nucleotide branch (Ricardo et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic conversion of glycolaldehyde and HCN to aminoimidazole", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and UV-active TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, anoxic cyanosulfidic pool"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide addition, reductive rearrangement, and ring closure in a cyanosulfidic mixture generate aminoimidazole-class heterocycles.", "reasoning": "Aminoimidazole-family intermediates, especially aminoimidazole carbonitrile derivatives, are well embedded in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry; representing this step as aminoimidazole production avoids the weaker claim of free imidazole directly arising in one jump while still connecting to histidine-like side-chain chemistry (Powner et al., 2009; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface HCN/formamide heterocycle chemistry to imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_017", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-assisted drying lagoon; concentrated formamide-rich films"}, "mechanism": "Aminoimidazole-class heterocycles undergo carbonylation/formylation and rearrangement in formamide-rich media to yield imidazole aldehyde derivatives.", "reasoning": "This is a bottleneck step but chemically better defined than previous unsupported free-imidazole routes because it starts from aminoimidazole-class material rather than bare HCN oligomers; formamide-mediated heterocycle functionalization is experimentally established in related systems, though specific access to imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde under prebiotic conditions remains partly speculative (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic condensation of imidazole-4-carboxaldehyde with pyruvate to imidazole pyruvate analog", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents"